==Finance==
The BBC has the largest budget of any UK broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.3 billion in 2007<ref>{{cite web | title = Annual Report and Accounts 2006/2007| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/annualreport/pdfs/bbcexec_eng.pdf | author = BBC | format = PDF | pages = p. 156 | accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> compared to £3.8 billion for [[British Sky Broadcasting]],<ref>{{cite web | title= Annual Report and Accounts 2007 | url = http://library.corporate-ir.net/library/10/104/104016/items/258443/AR07.pdf
 | author = BSkyB | authorlink = British Sky Broadcasting | format = PDF | pages = p. 115| accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> £1.9 billion for [[ITV]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Report and Accounts 2007 | url = http://www.investis.com/itv/storage/raccounts.pdf
 | author = ITV | authorlink = ITV plc | format = PDF | pages = p. 120 | accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> and £214 million in 2007 for [[GCap Media]] (the largest commercial radio broadcaster).<ref>{{cite web | title = Annual Report 2006/2007 | url = http://corporate.gcapmedia.com/assets/dynamic/39/files/gcap_media_ar07.pdf
 | author = GCap Media | authorlink = GCap Media | format = PDF | pages = p. 63 | accessdate= 2008-06-14}}</ref>

===Revenue===
{{update}}
{{see also|Television licence|Television licensing in the United Kingdom}}
[[Image:BBC income 2004 in GBP Redvers.png|right|325px]]

The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £139.50 per year per household (as of May 2008). Such a licence is required to operate a broadcast [[television]] receiver within the UK. The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law. A discount is available for households with only black-and-white television sets.   The revenue is collected privately and is paid into the central government [[Consolidated Fund]], a process defined in the [[Communications Act 2003]]. This ''TV Licensing'' collection is  currently carried out by Capita, an outside agency. Funds are then allocated by the Department of Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation. Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75 year olds.

Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years,<ref>{{cite web | title = Annual Report and Accounts 2004-2005 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/foi/docs/finance/annual_accounts/Annual_Accounts_2004-2005.pdf | author = BBC | format = PDF | pages = p. 94 | accessdate= 2006-07-06}}</ref> with [[BBC Worldwide]] contributing some £145&nbsp;million to the BBC's core public service business.

According to the BBC's 2005–2006 Annual Report,<ref>{{cite web | title = Annual Report and Accounts 2005-2006 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/foi/docs/annual_reports_and_reviews/annual_report_and_accounts/BBC_Annual_Report_2005_06.pdf | author = BBC | format = PDF | pages = pp. 103–104 | accessdate = 2007-01-21}}</ref> its income can be broken down as follows: 

* £3,100.6 million (£3.1bn) in licence fees collected from householders.
* £620.0M from BBC Commercial Businesses.
* £260.2M from the World Service, of which £239.1&nbsp;m is from grants (primarily funded by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office), £15.8&nbsp;m from subscriptions, and £5.3M from other sources.
* £24.2M from other income, such as providing content to overseas broadcasters and concert ticket sales.

The licence fee has, however, attracted criticism. It has been argued that in an age of multi stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate. The BBC's use of private sector company [[Capita Group]] to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2006/09/22/ftlicence22.xml | title = Why am I being hounded like this? | publisher = [[Telegraph]] | date = [[22nd Sept]] 2006 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref> The BBC uses an advertising campaign to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee. These letters and adverts have been criticised by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MPs [[Boris Johnson]] and [[Ann Widdecombe]], for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2005/05/26/do2602.xml | title = I won't pay to be abused by the BBC | publisher = [[Telegraph]] | date =  26 May 2005 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.dailyexpress.co.uk/posts/view/24455/BBC-bullies-shame-in-licence-fee-chaos | title = BBC BULLIES' SHAME IN LICENCE FEE CHAOS | publisher = [[Daily Express]] | date =  7 November 2007 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref> Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.tvlicensing.co.uk/index.jsp | title = TV Licensing | publisher = [[TV Licensing]] | date =  2 June 2008 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref> There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.spiderbomb.com/tv/ | title = Example of Licence Fee pressure group | publisher = [[Campaign to Abolish the Licence Fee]] | date =  2 June 2008 | accessdate = 2008-02-06}}</ref>

